voice_to_text: Parents, how did it feel when your child turned into a walking disaster? My 11 year old daughter started acting like a grown woman and I thought it was just early puberty stuff, but then I realized something much darker was happening. My daughter was one of those girls who hit puberty like a freight train. One month she was my little girl in Pokemon t shirts. The next month I was desperately searching the junior section because nothing in kids sizes would button across her chest. I started noticing the attention before I could pretend it wasn't happening. We were at target when she said casual as anything, that the man in electronics had followed us to three different aisles. She didn't sound scared, just stated it like a fact, like she was telling me it might rain. It got bad when she started consuming content that no 11 year old should even know existed. Her iPad history at 2:00am showed romance novels about CEOs and secretaries, bookmark folders labelled Dark Romance and Age Gap. She discovered Wattpad and archive of our own reading explicit stories about innocent girls and men who know better. Her YouTube algorithm had shifted completely. Makeup tutorials for that clean girl aesthetic. How to look expensive, feminine energy that drives men crazy. She was watching videos about how to walk in heels, how to make your voice sound more sultry, how to flirt without being obvious. When I tried to stop her from consuming That content. She turned into someone I didn't recognize. She started using therapy speak to manipulate every conversation. I was gaslighting her when I set boundaries, being toxic when I said no to crop tops. Emotionally abusive for taking her phone at night. She'd Learned these words somewhere and weaponized them perfectly. Her friend group shifted overnight. The girls her age were suddenly so immature and childish. Gravitated toward eighth graders and high schoolers who'd wave at her during pickup. Started lying with disturbing ease. She was at the library, but really at Starbucks with older kids. At Emma's house, but actually at the mall. She'd figured out how to delete specific texts while keeping others clear. Only certain parts of her history created fake contact names. Emma mom was really someone named Tyler. She started sitting differently, legs crossed like an adult. Hand gestures while talking that she'd copied from somewhere. At family dinners, she insert herself into adult conversations about work, drama, and relationships, offering advice like she was 30. When we visited relatives, she spent the entire time with the adults, laughing at jokes she shouldn't understand, making comments about wine and coffee preferences she didn't have. The secrets multiplied like cancer. Her phone became Fort Knox. Password changed weekly, face I D. Disabled so I couldn't use it. While she slept, she'd angle the screen away reflexively. Muscle memory from constant deception. I found out from another mom that my daughter had been telling everyone she was 16, not 11. With a whole fabricated backstory about being held back. Started lying about everything. Library visits that were really mall trips with high schoolers, study groups that didn't exist. Sleepovers at houses I never heard of. Her bedroom door stayed locked constantly. Music blasting to cover phone conversations. Stop talking to me entirely. Dinner became silent warfare. One word answers while scrolling under the table. Her former best friend's mom called concerned. Apparently, my daughter had told the girl she'd outgrown their friendship. At her spring concert, she wore the required black dress, but she'd altered it somehow. Taken in the waist, shortened the hem. She looked like a teenager, not an eleven year old. As she walked across the stage, I watched father's heads turn and follow her movement. These weren't strangers. They were soccer dads. Be a volunteer is my neighbor. Their gazes lingered a bit too long before they caught themselves. But what disturbed me most was her awareness of it. She wasn't innocent to the attention anymore. She expected it and seemed to feed off it. After the performance, she didn't run to me like the other kids ran to their parents. She stood with the older performers, laughing at something on someone's phone. When I finally got her attention, she rolled her eyes and mouth. Five more minutes, like I was embarrassing her. voice_to_text: When did your husband's female friend finally cross the line? My husband's friend Kate always had to be the main character in every situation. When someone else had good news, Kate suddenly had better news. At group dinners, she'd hijack any conversation within five minutes. I couldn't stand her, but I put up with it because she and Zach had been friends since college. After my husband and I announced our pregnancy at 12 weeks, things with Kate got really weird. Suddenly, Kate was everywhere we went sporting a small baby bump. She showed up at our favourite brunch spot rubbing her belly. She enrolled in our exact prenatal yoga class. She even switched to our O B. Practice. Nobody questioned it because these things happen and women get pregnant at the same time, she posted weekly bump photos on Instagram and everyone congratulated her just like they did me. Three months in, one of our friends mentioned something strange at a girls night. She's and Kate's belly looked bigger the previous Tuesday at book club than it did at Saturday's barbecue. When she brought it up, Kate burst into tears about how cruel it was to comment on a pregnant woman's body. She went on about water retention and bloating and how pregnant women deal with enough judgment without their friends piling on. Our friend felt terrible and apologized profusely while the rest of us comforted Kate. After that night, nobody dared mention anything about her appearance again. Even Though I started noticing her bump size seemed to fluctuate, too. That's when things got uncomfortable. Kate started making comments about how wild it was that we got pregnant around the same time. She'd joke about our babies being best friends, maybe even more than friends someday. Then the jokes got stranger, like when she said Pregnancy Brain made her forget exactly when she conceived and wasn't it funny how close our due dates were? She started showing up at every single appointment Zach and I had, always in the waiting room when we arrived, claiming her appointment was right before or after ours. During our maternity photo shoot at the park, she appeared with her own photographer, saying what a coincidence that she booked the same spot. The photographer later told me Kate had called asking what time we'd be there. Everything exploded at my baby shower. My sister threw this beautiful garden party with all our family and friends there to celebrate. Halfway through opening gifts, Kate stood up and clinked her glass to make an announcement. With tears streaming down her face, she placed her hand on her belly and said, I have the most wonderful news to share with everyone. Zack and I are having a baby together! The entire party gasped, and she continued with a huge smile, I know this is unconventional, but isn't it beautiful that our babies will be siblings?

voice_to_text: What's the creepiest display of intelligence you've seen by another human one? I knew a guy who worked retail and was able to memorize customer credit card numbers. 2. A friend once showed me his guidebook to how to handle his girlfriend. He'd taken notes on her likes and dislikes, what he'd given her, and precisely how she responded, which actions caused which responses in her, what phrases he could quote at her to yield particular responses, etcetera. And then sort of use the information he'd collected to write a little guide to expected outcomes of various things he does. So that he could diffuse her if she got mad at him, if she felt unloved, he had strategies for fixing the situation so he could go back to doing whatever he likes while she gets off his back. It was somewhere between oddly sweet and creepily manipulative. 3. My sister, hands down. And it's an ongoing thing. Dishwasher is broken. Ten literal minutes of YouTube later, she's got it figured out. The what, the how, the why, and it'll be fixed in half an hour if the parts are in stock at Lowe's. Car making a funny noise? Get her on Facetime, pop the hood, crank the engine, and she's got it located and id'd. And estimates from three local shops for you to pick from. Random archaeological discovery mentioned in passing on the daily M S N. Headlines. She read the journal article already and isn't it interesting? How that validates so and So's findings from his dig in Chile in the 80s. Crazy complicated, super esoteric recipe from Thailand she's never tried. I'll bet you $1,000 she'll glance at the recipe twice and whip out a version you could sell in a restaurant. She remembers your coworker's sister's boyfriend's birthday and that he really likes chocolate sprinkles, but not rainbow. She can get a feral dog eating out of her hand and get it to let her give it a bath and diagnose what's wrong with its back leg from 10 paces away. Her bosses at work keep trying to move her up the chain, but she's not interested because it'll cut into her jam making time or something. But they all come to her first when there's a question or a problem they can't fix. And they listen on the first go. Her husband says he's seen her ask the general manager what flavour of stupid he ate for breakfast this morning and seen him apologise for the error in judgement. She'll tell you she's not that smart. She just has a good memory. But I don't know, man. It's terribly handy to have her on my side, but if she ever decides to take over the world, we're all screwed. Four. Not creepy, but I knew a 14 year old who was helping his dad drywall a home. The kid looked at the shape of a staircase, looked at the drywall on the horses. Ready To cut, looked back at the staircase, then cut the drywall without a single measurement or marking. The drywall fit the staircase so perfectly it slid into place like it was snuggling the stairs. Not a single measurement. 5 when I was in med school, I was tangentially friends with a guy who never showed up to college at all. Skipped all lectures, called in sick for all lab and tutorial sessions. The night before second year finals he was around my house and said he had spent the last week watching every lecture at 2 x speed. Dude placed top 10 out of 300 students in every exam. And mind you, it wasn't just he remembered everything, but he had a functional, lateral applicable knowledge of all the stuff we had to know. Much better than most people who actually showed up. I always shudder to think that if he applied himself he would be a monster of a man, but dude was content to just chill. 6 I knew a lady who counted pills in a pharmacy basically her entire life. One time she looked at a container of ibuprofen that was supposed to have 100 pills in it and said it looked off. She recounted. And it had 99 pills in it. One less. My mind was blown.

voice_to_text: Fun fact, when John Krasinski was offered the role of Carter Rutherford in Leatherheads, he really wanted to take the job, but it meant he would have to cut his hair and therefore he'd have to wear a wig to film the last six episodes of Season 3 of the office. He pitched the idea of wearing a wig to the Office's showrunners, but Greg Daniels refused, saying he would know if John was wearing a wig. But rather than turn down the role, John went to the office's hair stylist, Kim Fairy, for help in secret. Kim had a Jim Halpert wig made for John and before filming one day, they secretly put the wig on and went and film the scenes for the day. After filming, John left the wig on and drove to Greg Daniels office and once again pitched all the reasons why you should let him wear a wig for the remaining episodes of the season. But Greg Daniels kept saying no.

And yes, this will allegedly be including AirPods and Apple Watches as well. The thing is, these pouches have always gotten a ton of backlash considering they cost millions of dollars. And if there's ever an emergency, it makes accessing your phone almost impossible because you have to go to one of these ports to unlock it. But now these schools in Texas are basically being given an ultimatum. They can either ban phones altogether, which no one wants, or they will have to start mass implementing these things within the next 90 days if they want to stay open. I mean, the crazy thing is it's not even just the students that are against using these pouches. It's mainly parents who are extremely concerned that they will not be able to get a hold of their child if an emergency happens. To make things worse, the company that manufactures these little bags is somewhat unethical. They are privately owned and are for profit. And ever since this Law passed. The company that manufactures them has a valuation of over $300 million. Dating, the person that came up with this idea that all students need to lock their phones up is getting insanely rich. So the claim that they are doing it so students will be able to focus on their studies more isn't really realistic at this point. The best decision might be to either leave Texas all together or to just get homeschooled.

voice_to_text: How did you learn your childhood passed away? I was sitting in my cubicle on the third floor of this boring office building downtown staring at spreadsheets and thinking about what to make for dinner. Around 2:30, I noticed my phone lighting up with calls. Three missed calls from Jackson Elementary. I figured my son Tommy forgot his lunch money again or maybe got in trouble for talking too much in class. Kid never stopped talking at home either. I stepped into the hallway to call them back. The secretary's voice sounded weird, shaky. She said there was an incident near the school and all parents needed to come to the community center on Oak Street immediately. When I asked what kind of incident, she just repeated the address and hung up. My hands started sweating. I grab my purse and told my supervisor I had a family emergency. The whole drive there, I kept thinking about how Tommy always forgot to look both ways before crossing streets. Maybe he got hit by a car walking to the corner store for chips. The community centre parking lot was chaos. Police cars everywhere, ambulances, news vans. Parents were running around screaming their kids names. I saw Missus Garcia from Tommy's class crying into her phone. Inside, they had tables set up with volunteers checking names off lists. I got in line behind this dad who was shaking so bad he could barely hold his. I d the volunteer at my table Was this young guy, maybe college age and he looks like he wanted to throw up. I gave him Tommy's full name, Thomas Mitchell, 4th grade, Missus Peterson's class. He flipped through papers, then called over an older woman. She had that look people get when they're about to tell you something terrible. She asked me to follow her to a smaller room. There were folding chairs in a circle and a box of tissues on every surface. That's when I knew. She sat me down and explained that there was a shooting at the park next to Tommy's school. The 4th grade classes were outside for recess when it happened. Some guy with mental problems started firing randomly at people walking by. Tommy had been playing on the monkey bars when it started. The other kids ran toward the school building, but Tommy must have gotten confused and ran the wrong way toward the fence, toward the shooter. The woman kept talking, but I stopped hearing words. Something about how brave the teachers were, how they tried to protect everyone, how the police got there fast. But all I could think about was Tommy on those monkey bars, probably showing off for his friends like he always did. I asked to see him. She said that wasn't possible right now, but they would arrange something later. She handed me a plastic bag with his backpack, same Pokemon backpack he begged me to buy at the start of the school. Year, the worst part wasn't even that moment. It was driving home and seeing his bike in the driveway, his cereal bowl still in the sink from breakfast, his homework spread out on the kitchen table because he'd insisted on finishing it that morning instead of the night before. I called my sister to come over because I couldn't be alone. When she got there, I was sitting on his bedroom floor holding his stuffed Dinosaur, the one he pretended he didn't sleep with.

voice_to_text: The story you'll never tell your kids. When I was 15, my older brother Jake was everyone's golden boy. Jake had this habit of borrowing my birthday and Christmas money, always promising to pay me back. Mom would hand me $50 for my birthday. Jake would ask for 20 by dinner, Christmas money from grandma, gone. By New Years, over three years, he'd systematically stolen almost $800 and laughed every time I asked for it back. And I discovered he was stealing more than money. I walked into his room looking for my calculator and found a box under his bed. Inside were my rare Pokemon cards that Grandpa gave me before he passed. I immediately checked eBay on his laptop and found his seller account, Jake the Great 99. He'd already sold half my collection for over $2,000, including Grandpa's prized Japanese Mew card. I confronted him immediately, tears streaming down my face. He shrugged and said, prove it, loser. I ran to mom crying, showed her the empty card binder, explained everything. Jay calmly followed me downstairs and told mom I'd probably lost them or sold them myself for money. He even suggested I was going through a troubled phase and making up stories for attention. Mom believed him instantly because perfect Jake would never lie to his little brother. That night, I planned my revenge. I knew three crucial things about Jake. He was bringing his new girlfriend, Lisa, over after school tomorrow. He was absolutely terrified. Of any spider or crawling insect. And our parents worked late every Wednesday. I spent the next week collecting daddy long legs from our basement, garage and shed. Every morning before school, I grab five or six and carefully store them in a large terrarium in my closet. I fed them fruit flies and made sure they stayed healthy and active. By Wednesday, I had 60 live spiders ready for deployment, all energetic and eager to explore new territory. Wednesday morning arrived. Jake left for school first, like always, bragging to his friends on the phone about his hot date. I stayed home sick with a convenient stomach bug and got to work immediately. I placed clusters of spiders in his dresser drawers, scattered individuals across his bed sheets, cut them between his pillows and saved the biggest group for his closet where he'd definitely look first when showing off his varsity jacket. I positioned myself in the hallway. When they arrived, Jake was in full show off mode, talking loud about his football scholarship offers from three different colleges. His girlfriend Lisa was clearly impressed, laughing at everything he said and touching his arm constantly. They headed straight to his room, promising to show her his trophy collection. I heard him say, let me just grab my varsity jacket to show you the patches, followed by the closet door creaking open. The scream that erupted from Jake was absolutely inhuman. High pitched fear filled. The kind of sound that Makes neighbors call police immediately. Lisa shrieked when she saw him stumbling backward, frantically brushing spiders off his precious jacket while more rained down from above. When Jake fell backward onto his bed in panic, dozens more spiders scattered in every direction. Lisa jumped onto his desk chair as Jake completely lost it, tears streaming down his face, hyperventilating as he swatted at spiders. Lisa demanded to know what was wrong with him, if he was having some kind of mental breakdown. Jake couldn't form coherent words, just kept pointing and sobbing like a terrified child. When she opened his dresser to get him a clean shirt, even more spiders poured out like a horror movie. She grabbed her bag and ran downstairs. Jake chased after her, still crying and begging her not to leave, trying to explain between sobs. From my bedroom window, I watched her speed away while Jake stood in our driveway having a complete emotional breakdown. Reputation destroyed forever. Lisa never spoke to him again and told everyone at school he was seriously disturbed.

Save your allowance money. No boy's gonna ask someone who looks like they got hit by the ugly stick. Mom would just sigh and change the subject for once, telling him to stop. College wasn't any better. Every time I came home for breaks, dad had new material. Still no boyfriend. Shocking. Maybe try lowering your standards. Desperate men exist somewhere. When my younger sister started dating in high school, he'd make comparisons. At least one of my daughters inherited her mother's good genes. After graduation, I moved across the city and got a job at Henderson Marketing. That's where I met Ryan from the accounting department. He was a sweet, quiet guy who always had kind words for everyone. We'd eat lunch together sometimes and he'd listen to me vent about difficult clients without judging. Ryan wasn't traditionally gorgeous. He wore thick glasses, kept his hair messy and dressed like comfort was his only priority. But he had this gentle smile that made me feel Safe and he never made me feel weird about my insecurities like other guys did. Six months into our friendship, I had one of those terrible weekends at home. Dad spent Sunday dinner making jokes about my eternal spinsterness in front of my sister's new boyfriend. I was so humiliated I could barely eat. That night lying in my old bedroom, I hatched a desperate plan. Monday morning I cornered Ryan by the coffee machine. This is going to sound insane, but would you pretend to be my boyfriend for one family dinner? My dad thinks I'm too hideous to ever find love and I just want to prove him wrong. Once I was talking fast, embarrassed. I'll pay for gas and buy you a nice dinner after to make up for the torture. Ryan didn't even hesitate. You don't need to pay me anything. When do we do this? The next Saturday, Ryan showed up at my apartment and I barely recognized him. He got a haircut, traded his usual wrinkled polo for a crisp button down shirt and he was holding a bouquet of flowers without his glasses. Apparently he bought contacts. He looked complete different, handsome even for your mom, he said, handing me the flowers. And you look beautiful, by the way. The drive to my parents house was nerve racking. I coached him on family details, but he seems surprisingly calm. Just be yourself, he said. Well, yourself but pretending to be crazy about me. He walked through my parents front door holding hands. Dad's face went completely blank. He stared at Ryan like he was trying to solve a math problem. Mom immediately perked up, clearly thrilled that I finally brought someone home. During dinner, Ryan was absolutely perfect. He complimented Mom's pot roast, dad about his weekend golf games and even help my little brother with his math homework. Every time dad tried to make one of his subtle digs about my appearance, Ryan would counter with something genuinely sweet. Actually, your daughter is the most beautiful woman I know, Ryan said when dad made a comment about me finally learning to use makeup properly. Inside and out, she's brilliant at her job, he told my parents. The way she handles difficult clients is incredible. She's patient and creative and she never gives up on people. Found myself staring at him across the dinner table, really looking at him maybe for the first time. The way his eyes lit up when he smiled, how gentle his hands were, when he jestered how he'd been nothing but kind to me for months without expecting anything in return. After dessert, dad actually shook Ryan's hand and said, you seem like a good man. Take care of her. I almost choked on my coffee walking back to his car. I was buzzing with adrenaline. That was amazing. You were so convincing. Dad actually liked you. Ryan stopped walking and turned to face me on the street. Light. I wasn't acting in there, he said quietly. I meant every single word. My heart started pounding. What do you mean? I mean, I've been crazy about you since your second week at the office. I mean, I bring you coffee every morning because I love seeing your face light up. I mean, when you smile at me, it's the best part of my entire day. Standing there in my parents driveway, Ryan took my hands and said, I wasn't pretending to be your boyfriend tonight. Turns out dad was wrong about everything. I didn't need to search far. My future husband was just three cubicles away, already seeing me as perfect.
